I believe this is the last exerpt that I will take from the article:<br><br>
   Most Americans heard of them in the 1980s-so-called &quot;bush vets&quot; or &quot;tripwire&quot; vets-&quot;wackos&quot; in the woods of the Pacific Northwest and the jungles of Hawaii who could not adjust to society.  The media made a mockery of men with genuine problems by focusing on a handful who exhibited bizarre behavior.<br>
   Gabriel, who wrote a landmark work on psychiatric war casualties, noted that wartime psychiatric disabilities were relatively light.  However, he concluded of the Vietnam scrvice &quot;There is no doubt that the chances that he would eventually suffer delayed psychiatric symptoms as a direct consequence of his experiences were much greater than in any of the previous wars.&quot;<br>
Recognition of this fact was long overdue in Congress.  It took Senate Veterans Affairs Committee Chairman Alan Cranston five attempts before the necessary legislation was passed.  On July 13, 1979, Carter signed RL. 96-22.  Its Sec. 103 provided for psychological counseling.  VKs Operation Outreach was launched that October.<br>
Intended for only two years, the program has been operating ever since.  In 1981, the Rehabilitation Counseling Service was created to direct the program.  Five years later, in 1986, the Vietnam Veteran Resource Center concept extended services to include employment, substance abuse and benefits counseling.<br>
Today, 206 Vet Centers exist nationwide.  Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) claims total 171,593 as of early 1997.  Some 91,605 Vietnam-era vets were drawing service-connected disability compensation for PTSD last year.<br>
As beneficial as the centers have been for thousands of vets, the medids exces sive emphasis exclusively on those who use them has created justifiable resent ment on the part of others.<br>
Vet Jerry Dickinson was exasperated: &quot;We're just ordinary guys.  We live ordinary lives; we have wives and kids and ordinary jobs.  We're okay.  But you never hear about us.  You only hear about the guys who are messed up' &quot;<br>
William K. Lane made this case most eloquently on the pages of the Wall Street journal.  &quot;The men I knew in Vietnam didn't hate each other because of race.  We were't on drugs.  We didn't murder civilians.  We didn't hate the Army or LBJ or our country.  We didn't feel America owed us a free ride because we spent time defending it.  We were our own 'support' group over there.  We don't need one here.<br>
&quot;Those who are legitimately disabled deserve a special, revered status in our society.  But can't we stop the fictional stereotyping that simply doesn't fit the majority of Vietnam veterans?<br>
&quot;Some of the bravest and best men that ever wore an American uniform fought in that war.  They deserve better than to be caricatured by Hollywood and represented in the media as a legion of losers.&quot;
